If you had an unpleasant experience eating here well sucks for you because mine was awesome! We came here for my birthday dinner and our reservation was for 10pm which I thought was a little odd because the restaurant hours says it closes at 10pm but they told us that the kitchen closes when everyone leaves which I thought was nice of them. We did have a reservation at 10pm but it took maybe 15 mintues for a table to free up so we spent our time looking around and getting a drink at the bar. We found street parking no problem but it was also night time which explains why, during the day might be more difficult and that's why they provide valet parking. I had a scotch on the rocks and waited to be seated. After being seated they told us they were sorry for the wait and brought out a little bite for us and it was a cake of some sort topped with salmon and caviar, it was to die for. Made up for the wait for sure. The service was amazing, I feel this is the only place I would ever give a 25% tip it was that great. The staff was friendly, overly polite and it was a dream. Felt like royalty here even after hours which I thought was great. We decided to go with the 5 course option and they adjust dish portions depending on how many courses you get. If you get less the portions are bigger and if you get more the portions are smaller so that's what I was expecting. The first course was appetizers and I got the lobster rissoto and it was amazing. The flavors were on point and the rice was perfectly cooked and the meat was tender. The next course was sea scallops and it was the greatest scallop I have ever had, it has ruined all scallops for me in the future. The next course was cornbread stuffed quail and it was tasty but I was on the fence deciding between the quail and the bison and I wish I had the bison, next time! The next course was the cheese course. I love cheese and I know what I like but they bring the cart next to your table and explain in detail all the cheeses they have to offer for your sampling pleasure. I got a goats milk gouda, creamy brie type cheese, a sheeps milk parmesan and some other french cheese who's name escapes me at the moment. They were all amazing and I love cheese and did I mention I like cheese? Anyway after that came dessert. I got macaroon ice cream sandwiches, strawberry, lemon and pistacio were among the flavors and they were all good but I was a little iffy on the lemon because it takes a very specific flavori profile when it comes to making lemon desserts for them to pass my tests. They also brought out little dessert bite samples of other things for us to share and that was amazing too and they were cute little bites like you'd eat at a tea party or something. SInce I came on my birthday they brought me a cake as well which was a marscapone cheesecake type thing and it was pretty tasty but I was way too into the other desserts. They ended the night by handing us our leftovers and giving us a cake for the next morning which was a pineapple and cream cheese cake which was super tasty the next morning. The bathrooms were spotless and I really enjoyed that. The bar had a great variety of single malt scotch and whiskeys. The people who go there are definitly the rich and fabulous of San Francisco and because of that you will encounter many rude people with smug senses of self importance but it comes with the territory of eating ridiculously well which I did for a night. The greatest service and meal of my entire life. I still dream of the food I ate there and I miss it to this day. Thank you Gary Danko for ruining all other restaurants for me.

Gary Danko is the classic representation of a umami experience in a city characterized as the epicenter of the culinary art. The food offers a distinctly contemporary take on San Francisco's émigré culture that is reflected in its molecular gastronomy. The seared sea scallops are juicy and brightly fused with pea purée and spring onions; a hint of exoticism is then added with mint and pickled radish. The lemon pepper duck breast winds up a haze of indistinct citrus flavors; and then comes the infrarrealist taste of the duck hash that brings reliable joy to this bewildering dish. The best is possibly the roasted quail: stuffed with mushroom ragout, leeks, quinoa, and foie gras. The quail is simple and complicated; with something of magic realism and more of the marvelous real that seamlessly blends the history and culture of the city, leaving you in a happy gastronomical and cultural stupor.

    Gary Danko has always been a reliable choice for high-end dining in SF. For those not in the know, you can eat there even if you don't have reservations (which can be difficult to get at times) by sitting at the bar (best bet is to show up at 5pm when they open). In any case, it had long been a favorite of ours. We ate there again last week. The "Dungeness Crab Salad with Citrus, Avocado and Meyer Lemon-Chive Vinaigrette" was wonderfully light and perfectly seasoned; the "Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls and Lettuce Cream" seemed like a poor man's imitation of Thomas Keller's Oysters and Pearls...for such a paltry portion, the dish was not rich enough to carry the flavors. My wife's "Savory Tart of of Spring Vegetables with Ricotta Cheese Mousse" was the biggest surprise of the evening. It was full-flavored but commendably light. Meanwhile, I was somewhat disappointed with my "Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Rhubarb". The flavors seemed almost tired...been there done that; my meal was redeemed by the "Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame Beans and Tarragon"...this was a decadently rich dish and the lobster was perfectly tender and sweet. I would have licked my plate if I had the chance. I am glad I didn't get my wife's "Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers and Mustard Sauce". The poached fish tasted soggy and bland, and the horseradish was not complimentary. My "Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Parsnip Purée and Roasted Grapes" was good but not great...the duck was cooked medium-well instead of medium-rare, but the duck leg confit hash was crispy and delicious. My wife's "Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Israeli Couscous, English Peas, Spring Onions, Artichokes and Mint" was perfectly cooked, but I preferred the flavor profiles of my "Seared Filet of Beef with Braised Celery, Potatoes, Bacon, Leeks and Bordelaise Crust". The celery was perfectly braised...it was tender yet retained some crunch while the beef was perfectly seasoned and cooked. We finally finished off our meal with the "Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces". The souffle was perfectly light and airy and was complimented well by the creme anglais and dark chocolate sauces. The mignardises made for a final temptation though I missed the meringue cookies. Of note, the valet parking is rather expensive at $11, and is added to the check. The total damage including a cocktail, coffee and capuccino came to about $300. This was a very nice meal and reinforced my faith in Gary Danko.

    Nestor, San Diego, CA
    7 friends
    4 reviews

    Share review

    Embed review

    6/2/2015

    1 check-in

    Gary Danko is the classic representation of a umami experience in a city characterized as the epicenter of the culinary art. The food offers a distinctly contemporary take on San Francisco's émigré culture that is reflected in its molecular gastronomy. The seared sea scallops are juicy and brightly fused with pea purée and spring onions; a hint of exoticism is then added with mint and pickled radish. The lemon pepper duck breast winds up a haze of indistinct citrus flavors; and then comes the infrarrealist taste of the duck hash that brings reliable joy to this bewildering dish. The best is possibly the roasted quail: stuffed with mushroom ragout, leeks, quinoa, and foie gras. The quail is simple and complicated; with something of magic realism and more of the marvelous real that seamlessly blends the history and culture of the city, leaving you in a happy gastronomical and cultural stupor.
